areaDesc.3: All city conveniences, adequate transportation, close to small park, paved streets
areaDesc.4: South of the area is occupied largely by cotton mill properties and people
areaDesc.14: Type of construction fairly uniform.  The area to the south is largely made up of mill houses of cheap construction.

areaDesc.3: All utilities, bus transportation, close to city park, zoned for strictly residential single family.
areaDesc.4: None
areaDesc.14: No houses have been lately offered for sale in this area.  The surrounding section is not much built up.  The eastern side has a rather steep slope.

areaDesc.3: Close to main business district.  All city conveniences
areaDesc.4: Industrial development along north and east.  Inadequate transportation
areaDesc.14: Northern part is gradually being taken over by negroes.  Southern part along Duke Street is considerably better.

areaDesc.3: Adjoining Duke University - all city conveniences - zoned for single family
areaDesc.4: Inadequate transportation - distance from business center
areaDesc.14: There are only four houses in this area.  It is a recent development occupied by doctors.  The homes are on very large lots, and are of the expensive type - $12000-$20000.  It adjoins the new Duke Univeristy grounds.

areaDesc.3: Close to main business distrcit, schools, all city conveniences
areaDesc.4: Negro section joining on south, encroachment of apartments and rooming houses and commercial district.
areaDesc.14: This is one of the older good residential sections with many large homes.  Encroachment of business district, however, will gradually change the grading.  The type of adjacent neighborhood is also against it.

areaDesc.3: All city conveniences, adequate transportation
areaDesc.4: Railroad track through center of area, many unpaved streets
areaDesc.14: Best part of the area is the western part around Dowd Street and on it.

areaDesc.3: Adequete transportation, city coveniences
areaDesc.4: Ditch running through area, trash dump located in area
areaDesc.14: This area occupied by negroes mostly of lower class. There are a few fairly decent houses on Club Boulevard.

areaDesc.3: Large lots, quiet, all utilities, school on 9th St, adequate transportation, park close.  In direction of city trend.
areaDesc.4: 3 miles from center of city - truck traffic? (There is an indication that the future may see East and West bound through truck traffic routed along Club Boulevard)
areaDesc.14: The better part of the area is that part extending from Maryland Avenue to Hillendale Road, along Club Boulevard.  That part of the area on 9th Street and on Club Boulevard fronting Watts Hospital not quite as desirable as other part of area.

areaDesc.3: All utilities, adequate transportation, close to park
areaDesc.4: Unpaved streets, distance to schools and community center
areaDesc.14: There is a golf course, well kept, almost adjoining this area.  There has been quite a bit of activity in sale of vacant lots here in the past few months.

areaDesc.3: Close to schools and community business center, all city conveniences, adequate transportation
areaDesc.4: Surrounded by cotton mill section and undesirable neighborhoods.  City not building in its direction.
areaDesc.14: This is an area of only two blocks in length and extending along Hyde Park Avenue.  Its main objectionable feature is the surroundings; however, it is far ahead in value, desirability, and appearance of the adjacent neighborhoods.

areaDesc.3: All city conveniences, fair transportation
areaDesc.4: Cemetery on north, and old amusement park
areaDesc.14: Best portion along Chapel Hill Road and part of James Street

areaDesc.3: Adequate Transportation, city conveniences
areaDesc.4: Adjoining cemetery, ditch through part of area
areaDesc.14: Eastern side of this area lies immediately adjoining area occupied by white people, and the same is true of the northern side. A large ditch is on the eastern side. Northern portion most desirable.

areaDesc.3: Has all city conveniences, paved streets, close to schools and community business center, walking distance of main business district.
areaDesc.4: Nothing particular; surrounding properties are old.  Tendency to industrial development along railroad in area to the east.
areaDesc.14: The area is fairly uniform and occupied by a good type of substantial middle-class citizen.  Cause for increase in predominating values is the fact that the past few years has seen quite a lot of new building in this area

areaDesc.3: All city conveniences, adequate transportation in eastern portion
areaDesc.4: Railroad and industrial development on north, also inadequate transportation in western portion
areaDesc.14: Best portion on west is Erwin Road and on south Duke University Road - Chapel Hill Street, Burch Street, and west end of Wilkerson Street.

areaDesc.3: Close to main business district.  All city conveniences.  Close to schools, adequate transportation.
areaDesc.4: Undesirable approach from three sides.
areaDesc.14: In this section are located the homes of some of the wealthiest families in the city, mostly on Duke Street and Hill Street.  That part of the area along Vickers Avenue, Shepherd Street, and Arnett Avenue consists of the lower priced homes.  The desirability of the section is largely maintained by the presence of these higher-priced homes, and it is hardly possible that any future development will be other than in the medium to lower-priced dwellings.

areaDesc.3: Close to school
areaDesc.4: Inadequate transportation, railroad track along north, un-paved streets
areaDesc.14: This is a section composed largely of cheaply built shacks - very poor class of tenants

areaDesc.3: All city conveniences, adequate transportation, schools located in area, also community business center.
areaDesc.4: Industrial area along railroad tracks on North and West.

6.a: Small singles and some large singles

areaDesc.14: White population largely on McMannen Street for about 2 blocks South of railroad and some on South Street, and on McMannen Street are several fairly nice homes. This was formerly a good white residential street but negroes are gradually taking up the area.

areaDesc.3: Adequate transportation, all city conveniences, negro college located in area.
areaDesc.4: Lack of uniformity in properties, unpaved streets

5.a: Negro professional men, insurance men, mechanics, laborers

areaDesc.14: In this section live most of the negroes with better incomes.  There are some nice residences in the area but where you find one good one there is likely to be adjoining it on either or both sides a house of much lower grade in quality.

areaDesc.3: Adequate transportation, western part adjoins Junior and Senior High School.
areaDesc.4: Railroad track through southwestern part and industrial activity along the track.  Large low-lying tract between railroad and Duke Street.
areaDesc.14: New construction along Roxboro Road and Club Boulevard, these two streets being about the best in the area.

areaDesc.3: Adequacy of every utility - schools - college
areaDesc.4: None

6.a: Singles & Duplexes & apts. to Urban St. Beyond Urban zoned for singles

9.c: None for sale except vacant lots

areaDesc.14: The southern part of this area is the older part and the section was started about 30 years ago.  It is continuing northward-it being adjacent to the Women's College of Duke University is considered in its favor.  Many of the faculty members of the college own homes in the area and others rent.   There are several apartments and duplexes in the area and several duplexes have recently been built, but this has not had any detrimental effect on the area.  The area probably has as little sales resistance as any in the city.

areaDesc.3: Adequate transportation, community business center located on 9th Street near the railroad trach, schools and churches in area.
areaDesc.4: Cotton mill located in area, railroad track adjoins on south.

5.a: Cotton mill workers, mechanics, clerks, etc

areaDesc.14: There are two cotton mills located along the railroad tracks and probably 50% of the residences in the area are owned by the mill people and rented to their employees.  This applies largely to the western side of the area, west of Broad Street.

areaDesc.3: Adequate transportation - all city conveniences - school in area - also community business center.
areaDesc.4: Cotton mill on Maple Street on western side of area - industrial development along railroad trrack in center of area and also on western side - unpaved streets.
areaDesc.14: Western part of area close to main business district.  Many old large houses.  Properties on Cleveland, Roxboro, Markham, and Holloway is better portion.  Eastern part is in East Durham and not thickly populated.

areaDesc.3: All city conveniences, adequate transportation
areaDesc.4: Cotton mill and other industrial plants located on railroad
areaDesc.14: Northwest part of area occupied by negroes. At junction of Angier and Main is lare cotton mill. Mills also located on railroad track north of Main Street.

areaDesc.3: Public park, restricted covenants and deeds, adequate utilities, zoned for single family, minimum lot 75 feet wide
areaDesc.4: Distance to school, inadequate transportation, gas only in part

5.a: Professional men, business Executives, college professors

areaDesc.14: This is one of the best residential sections in Durham and has enjoyed a very healthy activity recently.  The population is substantial and is composed of those with good incomes.  Its distance from schools and business center does not detract from it.
